##Dialysis patient in Hubei Province: Ride 30 km to the hospital for quarantine at 1.30 am

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

Phoenix News Client, produced by Phoenix Network Studio on Earth

Open the Phoenix News client, search "on earth" and follow

Today is World Kidney Disease Day. For the past 50 days, dialysis patients in Hubei have been in a life-and-death situation.

On January 20, academician Zhong Nanshan identified the new coronavirus as "human-to-human" . On the 23rd, the city of Wuhan was closed. The epidemic situation of NCP is very serious. Many hospitals in Wuhan and other cities in Hubei have been requisitioned to be designated hospitals for NCP. There are 55 hospitals in Wuhan alone. As more beds are made available for new coronary pneumonia patients, those who are not new coronary patients, especially those with acute or chronic kidney failure and uremia, become a special group.

There are nearly 35,000 members of this special group in Hubei.

Xin Xin, who has lived in Wuhan for 13 years, lives alone in a 10 square meter bedroom. Three times a week, without a break, she took a bus to the nearby central war zone General Hospital for four hours of dialysis.

It's the most important thing in her life.

Born in Rural Ensch, Hubei Province in 1985, she was diagnosed with kidney failure at the age of 20 and developed uremia two years later. In 2007, a death row inmate in her hometown offered to donate two kidneys to her, and they were completely matched, and enough donations were made for the upcoming transplant. But fate played a joke on her, and the doctor told her that even if she did, the success rate was only about 50 percent.

She eventually passed up the opportunity and has been living on a dialysis machine in Wuhan ever since.

At first, each dialysis cost about 500 yuan. Later, the policy is good, most of the expenses can be reimbursed, each year to pay 10,000 yuan. She has no job, no steady income, and she's under a lot of stress. But life, it just goes on.

It never occurred to her that her life had anything to do with new crown pneumonia.

On Jan. 23, Wuhan was closed to public transportation, and until the community helped arrange the transportation, I rode my bike to dialysis, which took longer, and I felt tired, but I lived close to the hospital, so it was okay.

On January 29, at 2:30 p.m. , she received a message from a patient: "The hospital has been requisitioned (for new patients with pneumonia) , you hurry up, or there will be no place for Dialysis Tomorrow! "

"At that time flustered, dialysis is to maintain life, do not penetrate will die. " Heart pack on the back to the hospital.

To the hospital, the Department director let them find their own "next home" , if not, the hospital to find ways to help turnover. Some of the patients are not convinced, asked "are we to give up the lives of these people? " Heart voice also feel this group has been ignored. But she dared not pin her hopes on an uncertain status quo. When she learned that dialysis places were still available at the Va Hospital, 15 kilometers from here, she and four kidney friends cycled there to fight for them.

The empty streets of Wuhan are deserted, with five dialysis patients wearing face masks, Gasp, and riding shared bicycles. After more than a decade of dialysis, their bodies are weakened. I couldn't ride anymore. I just sat on the side of the road, breathing. The heart sounds suddenly feel desolate: "This disease originally lets the person be disheartened and cold, add epidemic situation, we more do not see hope. "

Fortunately, nearly 30 kilometers round trip did not run in vain, the VA hospital took them in. Many of her elderly patients are not so lucky, they do not use Wechat, and even rarely use mobile phones, the hospital was requisitioned news, only the next day to the hospital dialysis to know. She doesn't know where they went.

Two years ago, Xin Sheng bought a box of 50 surgical masks. By February 5th, she had a dozen or so left, barely enough to last more than a week. Later, a public interest organization for dialysis patients in Wuhan to obtain a part of the mask resources, but also can only last a few more days.

Heart says, go out dialytic since be in order to save a life, it is to put oneself in a dangerous antinomy position: "BE AFRAID NOT BY UREMIA poison to die, be poisoned by virus to die. "

Guangyao thought he was fine until the CT scan and the diagnosis from the designated hospital were confirmed.

Guangyao, 28, lives in a township in Xiantao, Hubei Province. At 18, he was diagnosed with chronic glomerulonephritis and worked in Wenzhou with his parents. His condition deteriorated and he was diagnosed with uremia. Started dialysis at home in 2013.

Guangyao onset of 120 pounds, began to do dialysis 170 pounds, the extra weight is basically all water. Hormone drugs had left a marked mark on his body, and his face and stomach were markedly different from the rest of his body, even after dialysis had removed large amounts of toxins and water. He had a lot of stretch marks on his back and arms. All these years he couldn't find a proper job, couldn't get back into society, he was desperate.

On February 11 this year, the hospital took a CT scan of a patient in the dialysis room. Guangyao was identified as a suspected case and was admitted to the isolation ward of Xiantao Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine. Subsequent viral nucleic acid tests were positive.

Guangyao became a "double patient" .

He has no fever, no other obvious symptoms, and it's not clear when he contracted the virus.

He just felt that at the age of 28, he couldn't find a job, he had to work for his old father to make a living, and his life was pathetic.

Years ago, Guangyao often played cards with his friends in the hotel. January 19, December twenty-five, he felt a little chest tightness, not breathing freely. Went to the hospital, took a film, the doctor diagnosed as "pneumonia" , gave him a little medicine. After half a month, the symptoms were almost gone. And there was no delay in dialysis.

He later realised that he might have contracted new pneumonia as early as January 19. The infection could be in the hospital dialysis room.

■ The isolation ward where Kuan Yew lives.

In the isolation ward of Xiantao Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine, the hospital guarantees three meals and normal dialysis treatment. He spent his days in the House under routine medical treatment and observation, leaving the ward only after dialysis and boiling water.

The constant updates on the death toll on television have rattled and worried Guangyao, who doesn't even want to play mobile games.

March 9th was the 28th day of his isolation. During the hospital has been cured and discharged, Guangyao slowly saw hope. When you think of dialysis patients who are younger than you, you think, "it's no big deal, " "it's no use thinking about it. ".
He has adapted to the days of isolation and thinks he will be out of the hospital soon.

On the afternoon of January 23, Lin Hui hung up on his brother-in-law with great care.

That day, the brother-in-law of long-term cough gives Lin Hui to call, he wants to go to a hospital, hope nephew drives to send a while. Lin Hui rebuffed. He is not to disregard relatives, but his dialysis 7 years, the body "can not bear. ". The closure of the city of Wuhan, just 20 minutes from Huanggang, made him extra cautious.

A few days later, he was diagnosed with "new pneumonia" and transferred to Florida Dabie Mountains Medical Center in Little Tangshan, Huanggang. Lin Hui felt that the choice was right at that time. As a very vulnerable dialysis patient, he was glad that he was not involved in a storm of extremely tight medical resources during the emergency period.
The paramedics at the door of the CT room.

On the evening of February 15, the People's Hospital of Huangzhou District, Huanggang, informed all dialysis patients that they had to be placed in a centralized isolation at the hospital that night.

That night, Lin Hui brought a set of toiletries and two sets of clothes, riding an electric bike to pick up the patients, ran nearly 30 kilometers. Didn't get to the hospital till 1:30 in the morning.

"outside the situation is very tense, we live in the hospital, as usual dialysis, feel fine. ". However, a few days later, Lin Hui found something strange: "a shift of dialysis patients are missing, after two days of nurses are missing. " Originally in the dialysis room to work 11 nurses, only one. Lin Hui has no way to verify what happened.

■ The nurse places the patient's lunch box on a chair.

Dialysis nurses began to be seconded from other departments to "chase the ducks on the shelves. ". Sticking the wrong needle bleeding, dialysis machine operation is not skilled, often let some older dialysis patients angry. Many dialysis patients are already anemic, and they are particularly sensitive to bleeding.

During isolation, whenever someone in the dialysis room has a fever, all patients are retested. Lin Hui went through three screenings, 20 days of time, the lung CT alone, took 3 times.

Lin Hui, a 34-year-old former businessman, set up shop in Shenzhen with relatives in 2005 and bought a restaurant a few years later. It wasn't until 2013 that he learned he had uremia because of a "lingering" cold. He lost money to put the shop out, back home to recuperate, dialysis.

In his opinion, working seven or eight hours a day without food or drink is the most difficult for the medical staff. He hoped the disease would pass and that the angels in white who had risked their lives to take care of the sick would be safe.

On the morning of January 23, Tiansheng took the subway line 2 to Wuhan Union Hospital for Dialysis. At 10 am, public transport in Wuhan was suspended. He ate a full meal near noon, and it took him all afternoon to get back to his house on Zangyong Island. Normally less than an hour away, the 41-year-old dialysis patient walked and biked for nearly six hours.

■ The dialysis room where Tiansheng is.

On the eve of the Lunar New Year, Tiansheng packed his bags, and his big brother drove him to the hotel near the Union hospital. The nearby restaurants and supermarkets are almost all closed. New Year's Eve dinner and New Year's Day breakfast, lunch, three consecutive meals, he was in the only nearby convenience store to solve, eat soy milk and steamed stuffed Bun.

On the evening of the first day of the Lunar New Year, the hotel was closed. In desperation, Tiansheng had to live in a bed and breakfast, 15 minutes away from the hospital. Property requirements, no matter what the status of the patient, can not live in the area. Worried about their "homeless" , Tiansheng did not tell the owner of his home is dialysis patients, only said to Wuhan "business. ". Even though he was carrying a "health certificate" from the hospital in advance.

For the first week, there was almost nothing to eat. Tiansheng took a simple cooking pot and ate noodles every day. One day there is no way, he contacted his doctor in the Union hospital students, looking for a nurse to get two boxes of food emergency. He ate two boxes of lunch for two days.

More and more strict inspection at the gate of the residential area, even with a temporary residence permit, security still questioned him why every two days to go out. He went to the hospital every day for dialysis and came back carefully. In a week, he lost seven pounds.

■ meals from the hostel owner.

On February 10, Wuhan New Crown Patients "should be collected, to see a doctor, " Tiansheng felt that his identity as a dialysis patient safe, to explain their situation with the boss and the property. The bed-and-breakfast owner delivers a meal to him every day at noon. Sometimes there is a little food left in the day, and in the evening, he makes a face to deal with it.

But since January 25, the daily price of 120 yuan, so that the current only low-income days sheng a little bit too much.

Tiansheng had a history of allergic nephritis for 10 years. After graduating from university in 2003, he studied design and found good job opportunities. But because of health reasons, he had to "resign to rest for a year" , until 2015 to resign completely. Started Dialysis in 2016.

In the eyes of his family, his illness has also become an unspeakable "problem. ". Big sister scolded him "should not get this disease" , "disease is also your own problem. ". He had broken off relations with his sister and was spending less and less time with the rest of the family. He hopes he can find the right "other half" among kidney friends, two people support each other for the rest of their lives.

At 12, Ruyun had diabetes. At Seventh grade, she took only a week of classes before dropping out of school to work with her family.

At 23, she married, and the following year, she miraculously gave birth. During pregnancy, diabetes causes kidney failure. Despite the hospital's objection, "do not want to remove the child" , want to use their own life to exchange for the child's life. After a struggle between nephrology and obstetrics, she went on dialysis twice and had a c section at the end of the month, giving birth.

Since then, Ruyun has been on dialysis for nine years. She thought about suicide, she thought about divorce. She once told her lover: "You're young, so I'm like this. You get the divorce done, I'll just sign it. I don't want to drag my family down with me. " He told her to just live.

Gradually, as Yun felt that he had to live for his children, through that period of gloomy days.

On a hospital bed.

It's like home in Wuhan, Huangpi District District. Last November, when she was out buying breakfast, she accidentally broke a ligament. After discharge home, Wuhan epidemic is increasingly serious, Huangpi District Township village management is very strict. The village secretary told her that if she went out for dialysis, she might not come back. At this point, if Yun's long-term catheter also appeared problem, must go to the hospital.

Helpless, her husband accompanied as Yun to Huangpi District People's Hospital in hospital, that day is the second day of the Lunar New Year.

The canteen and the convenience store were closed, and they had a tough time, eating only one meal of instant noodles a day. After the hospital cafeteria opened, each meal cost 25 yuan, which was too expensive. A box lunch, two people push to push each other do not want to eat.

A nurse brought a cooking pot, they bought Rice, plus their own vegetables, secretly cooking in the house to eat. See with the department of many elderly people eat three times a day instant noodles, such as Yun will also take care of them, make more food to share with everyone, together through the difficulties.

The shadow of death is always passing by. With the ward of the elderly arm arteriovenous Fistula blocked, the hospital did not have enough conditions to dredge, made a temporary tube. But because the blood is thick, he eats the food such as instant noodles every day, the temporary tube is also blocked. The old man goes home to die. A piece of dialysis of an aunt, the first day with such as Yun talk, the next day at noon people died. One day, a nurse told her that six dialysis patients were gone in one day. Life is too fragile, that day is like the heart of the most collapsed.

The hospital has to cover the cost of hospitalization every 14 days. So far, the couple has spent nearly 4,000 yuan on hospital bills alone.

After getting uremia, a lot of people will cast strange eyes, fortunately, there is a family not abandoned. But her husband had to take care of her, and neither of them could work, leaving their elderly parents to fend for themselves.

Deep Down, Ruyun felt sorry for her parents.

Yu Mo has been in Wuhan Light Valley Hospital Dialysis. For a long time after the city was shut down, her dialysis wasn't affected much. She thought it was gonna be like this forever.

On Feb. 12, before going to bed, she received a message from a patient on her wechat group: from Feb. 13, Guanggu Sanyuan no longer accepts dialysis patients. I haven't slept all night. Early the next morning, Yu Mo and his patients rushed to the hospital. Medical staff are busy renovating dialysis rooms, let them go to Wuhan Third Hospital Shouyiyuan district for CT examination, queuing for registration.

■ On the morning of Feb. 13, Yu and fellow patients sought dialysis help at Guanggu hospital.

After a long day and a CT scan. It wasn't until Feb. 15 that Yu and his patients were given new dialysis quotas and given dialysis at night, when the original dialysis time should have been the morning before. With medical resources so tight, dialysis, which was supposed to last four hours three times a week, has been reduced to three and a half hours twice a week.

Dialysis Day, she set off at 5 pm, take a friend's car two hours round trip to Wuhan Third Hospital Shouyiyuan district, home in the early morning. To help pay for the gas, she and two other patients each paid 15 yuan for the trip.

In the new hospital dialysis for the second time, Yu Mo midway suddenly felt strong discomfort, his blood pressure has not measured out, she asked the nurse to help back to stop dialysis. She lost consciousness before she could tell the nurse that she was going to faint. When I woke up, all the other patients were gone. In the dialysis room, there's only one other patient waiting for him. What a Dead Tone.

Dialysis takes a lot out of the body. After returning home every night, a strong sense of hunger urged Yu to replenish energy, but insufficient dialysis also made it difficult for toxins and water to accumulate and get out of the body. Barely eat something at night, the body uncomfortable and serious insomnia, Yu Mo began to take valium to sleep easier. Her days and nights began to turn upside down, and only two days after each dialysis, there was significant swelling on her face and body. The headache also began to torment Yu Mo.. She thinks it's a vicious circle. Continuing high potassium, phosphorus and parathyroid levels can lead to serious complications and life threatening conditions.

After eight dialysis sessions, Yu and his fellow patients saw plenty of empty seats on the ward.

Dialysis patients in Hubei Province, in the early spring of 2020, seem to have experienced a winter.

He is not to disregard relatives, but his dialysis 7 years, the body "can not bear. ". The closure of the city of Wuhan, just 20 minutes from Huanggang, made him extra cautious.

A few days later, he was diagnosed with "new pneumonia" and transferred to Florida Dabie Mountains Medical Center in Little Tangshan, Huanggang. Lin Hui felt that the choice was right at that time. As a very vulnerable dialysis patient, he was glad that he was not involved in a storm of extremely tight medical resources during the emergency period.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The paramedics at the door of the CT room.

On the evening of February 15, the People's Hospital of Huangzhou District, Huanggang, informed all dialysis patients that they had to be placed in a centralized isolation at the hospital that night.

That night, Lin Hui brought a set of toiletries and two sets of clothes, riding an electric bike to pick up the patients, ran nearly 30 kilometers. Didn't get to the hospital till 1:30 in the morning.

"outside the situation is very tense, we live in the hospital, as usual dialysis, feel fine. ". However, a few days later, Lin Hui found something strange: "a shift of dialysis patients are missing, after two days of nurses are missing. " Originally in the dialysis room to work 11 nurses, only one. Lin Hui has no way to verify what happened.

The paramedics at the door of the CT room.

" Originally in the dialysis room to work 11 nurses, only one. Lin Hui has no way to verify what happened.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
■ The nurse places the patient's lunch box on a chair.

Dialysis nurses began to be seconded from other departments to "chase the ducks on the shelves. ". Sticking the wrong needle bleeding, dialysis machine operation is not skilled, often let some older dialysis patients angry. Many dialysis patients are already anemic, and they are particularly sensitive to bleeding.

During isolation, whenever someone in the dialysis room has a fever, all patients are retested. Lin Hui went through three screenings, 20 days of time, the lung CT alone, took 3 times.

Lin Hui, a 34-year-old former businessman, set up shop in Shenzhen with relatives in 2005 and bought a restaurant a few years later. It wasn't until 2013 that he learned he had uremia because of a "lingering" cold. He lost money to put the shop out, back home to recuperate, dialysis.

In his opinion, working seven or eight hours a day without food or drink is the most difficult for the medical staff. He hoped the disease would pass and that the angels in white who had risked their lives to take care of the sick would be safe.

On the morning of January 23, Tiansheng took the subway line 2 to Wuhan Union Hospital for Dialysis. At 10 am, public transport in Wuhan was suspended. He ate a full meal near noon, and it took him all afternoon to get back to his house on Zangyong Island. Normally less than an hour away, the 41-year-old dialysis patient walked and biked for nearly six hours.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
■ The dialysis room where Tiansheng is.

On the eve of the Lunar New Year, Tiansheng packed his bags, and his big brother drove him to the hotel near the Union hospital. The nearby restaurants and supermarkets are almost all closed. New Year's Eve dinner and New Year's Day breakfast, lunch, three consecutive meals, he was in the only nearby convenience store to solve, eat soy milk and steamed stuffed Bun.

On the evening of the first day of the Lunar New Year, the hotel was closed. In desperation, Tiansheng had to live in a bed and breakfast, 15 minutes away from the hospital. Property requirements, no matter what the status of the patient, can not live in the area. Worried about their "homeless" , Tiansheng did not tell the owner of his home is dialysis patients, only said to Wuhan "business. ". Even though he was carrying a "health certificate" from the hospital in advance.

For the first week, there was almost nothing to eat. Tiansheng took a simple cooking pot and ate noodles every day. One day there is no way, he contacted his doctor in the Union hospital students, looking for a nurse to get two boxes of food emergency. He ate two boxes of lunch for two days.

More and more strict inspection at the gate of the residential area, even with a temporary residence permit, security still questioned him why every two days to go out. He went to the hospital every day for dialysis and came back carefully. In a week, he lost seven pounds.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
■ meals from the hostel owner.

On February 10, Wuhan New Crown Patients "should be collected, to see a doctor, " Tiansheng felt that his identity as a dialysis patient safe, to explain their situation with the boss and the property. The bed-and-breakfast owner delivers a meal to him every day at noon. Sometimes there is a little food left in the day, and in the evening, he makes a face to deal with it.

But since January 25, the daily price of 120 yuan, so that the current only low-income days sheng a little bit too much.

Tiansheng had a history of allergic nephritis for 10 years. After graduating from university in 2003, he studied design and found good job opportunities. But because of health reasons, he had to "resign to rest for a year" , until 2015 to resign completely. Started Dialysis in 2016.

In the eyes of his family, his illness has also become an unspeakable "problem. ". Big sister scolded him "should not get this disease" , "disease is also your own problem. ". He had broken off relations with his sister and was spending less and less time with the rest of the family. He hopes he can find the right "other half" among kidney friends, two people support each other for the rest of their lives.

At 12, Ruyun had diabetes. At Seventh grade, she took only a week of classes before dropping out of school to work with her family.

At 23, she married, and the following year, she miraculously gave birth. During pregnancy, diabetes causes kidney failure. Despite the hospital's objection, "do not want to remove the child" , want to use their own life to exchange for the child's life. After a struggle between nephrology and obstetrics, she went on dialysis twice and had a c section at the end of the month, giving birth.

Since then, Ruyun has been on dialysis for nine years. She thought about suicide, she thought about divorce. She once told her lover: "You're young, so I'm like this. You get the divorce done, I'll just sign it. I don't want to drag my family down with me. " He told her to just live.

Gradually, as Yun felt that he had to live for his children, through that period of gloomy days.

Gradually, as Yun felt that he had to live for his children, through that period of gloomy days.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On a hospital bed.

It's like home in Wuhan, Huangpi District District. Last November, when she was out buying breakfast, she accidentally broke a ligament. After discharge home, Wuhan epidemic is increasingly serious, Huangpi District Township village management is very strict. The village secretary told her that if she went out for dialysis, she might not come back. At this point, if Yun's long-term catheter also appeared problem, must go to the hospital.

Helpless, her husband accompanied as Yun to Huangpi District People's Hospital in hospital, that day is the second day of the Lunar New Year.

The canteen and the convenience store were closed, and they had a tough time, eating only one meal of instant noodles a day. After the hospital cafeteria opened, each meal cost 25 yuan, which was too expensive. A box lunch, two people push to push each other do not want to eat.

A nurse brought a cooking pot, they bought Rice, plus their own vegetables, secretly cooking in the house to eat. See with the department of many elderly people eat three times a day instant noodles, such as Yun will also take care of them, make more food to share with everyone, together through the difficulties.

The shadow of death is always passing by. With the ward of the elderly arm arteriovenous Fistula blocked, the hospital did not have enough conditions to dredge, made a temporary tube. But because the blood is thick, he eats the food such as instant noodles every day, the temporary tube is also blocked. The old man goes home to die. A piece of dialysis of an aunt, the first day with such as Yun talk, the next day at noon people died. One day, a nurse told her that six dialysis patients were gone in one day. Life is too fragile, that day is like the heart of the most collapsed.

The hospital has to cover the cost of hospitalization every 14 days. So far, the couple has spent nearly 4,000 yuan on hospital bills alone.

After getting uremia, a lot of people will cast strange eyes, fortunately, there is a family not abandoned. But her husband had to take care of her, and neither of them could work, leaving their elderly parents to fend for themselves.

Deep Down, Ruyun felt sorry for her parents.

Yu Mo has been in Wuhan Light Valley Hospital Dialysis. For a long time after the city was shut down, her dialysis wasn't affected much. She thought it was gonna be like this forever.

On Feb. 12, before going to bed, she received a message from a patient on her wechat group: from Feb. 13, Guanggu Sanyuan no longer accepts dialysis patients. I haven't slept all night. Early the next morning, Yu Mo and his patients rushed to the hospital. Medical staff are busy renovating dialysis rooms, let them go to Wuhan Third Hospital Shouyiyuan district for CT examination, queuing for registration.

Yu Mo has been in Wuhan Light Valley Hospital Dialysis. For a long time after the city was shut down, her dialysis wasn't affected much. She thought it was gonna be like this forever.

On Feb. 12, before going to bed, she received a message from a patient on her wechat group: from Feb. 13, Guanggu Sanyuan no longer accepts dialysis patients. I haven't slept all night. Early the next morning, Yu Mo and his patients rushed to the hospital. Medical staff are busy renovating dialysis rooms, let them go to Wuhan Third Hospital Shouyiyuan district for CT examination, queuing for registration.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
■ On the morning of Feb. 13, Yu and fellow patients sought dialysis help at Guanggu hospital.

After a long day and a CT scan. It wasn't until Feb. 15 that Yu and his patients were given new dialysis quotas and given dialysis at night, when the original dialysis time should have been the morning before. With medical resources so tight, dialysis, which was supposed to last four hours three times a week, has been reduced to three and a half hours twice a week.

Dialysis Day, she set off at 5 pm, take a friend's car two hours round trip to Wuhan Third Hospital Shouyiyuan district, home in the early morning. To help pay for the gas, she and two other patients each paid 15 yuan for the trip.

In the new hospital dialysis for the second time, Yu Mo midway suddenly felt strong discomfort, his blood pressure has not measured out, she asked the nurse to help back to stop dialysis. She lost consciousness before she could tell the nurse that she was going to faint. When I woke up, all the other patients were gone. In the dialysis room, there's only one other patient waiting for him. What a Dead Tone.

Dialysis takes a lot out of the body. After returning home every night, a strong sense of hunger urged Yu to replenish energy, but insufficient dialysis also made it difficult for toxins and water to accumulate and get out of the body. Barely eat something at night, the body uncomfortable and serious insomnia, Yu Mo began to take valium to sleep easier. Her days and nights began to turn upside down, and only two days after each dialysis, there was significant swelling on her face and body. The headache also began to torment Yu Mo.. She thinks it's a vicious circle. Continuing high potassium, phosphorus and parathyroid levels can lead to serious complications and life threatening conditions.

After eight dialysis sessions, Yu and his fellow patients saw plenty of empty seats on the ward.

Dialysis patients in Hubei Province, in the early spring of 2020, seem to have experienced a winter.
